SIMPLE: hartshorn
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hartshorn
<hw>Harts"horn`</hw> <pr>(-h⟦ocir⟧rn`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The horn or antler of the hart, or male red deer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Spirits of hartshorn (see below); volatile
salts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hartshorn plantain</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an
annual species of plantain (<spn>Plantago Coronopus</spn>); -- called
also <altname>buck's-horn</altname>.</cd> <au>Booth.</au> --
<col><b>Hartshorn shavings</b></col>, <cd>originally taken from the
horns of harts, are now obtained chiefly by planing down the bones of
calves. They afford a kind of jelly.</cd> <au>Hebert.</au> --
<col><b>Salt of hartshorn</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an impure
solid carbonate of ammonia, obtained by the destructive distillation of
hartshorn, or any kind of bone; volatile salts.</cd> <au>Brande &
C.</au>-- <col><b>Spirits of hartshorn</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>,
<cd>a solution of ammonia in water; -- so called because formerly
obtained from hartshorn shavings by destructive distillation. Similar
ammoniacal solutions from other sources have received the same
name.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 673 pr=JMD --></p>

<p><ent>Hart's-tongue</ent>⟦br⟧
